87–Male":"1287–Deceased","1289–1304":"1289–1304","1297–1327":"1297–1327","–1337":"–1337","1282–1368":"1282–1368","–Female":"Deceased","1328–Female":"1328–Deceased","1260–1355":"1260–1355","1265–1297":"1265–1297","1297":"1297","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","1284":"1284","1382":"1382","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","1304":"1304","1368":"1368","about 1328":"about 1328","1355":"1355","1289":"1289","1453":"1453","1265":"1265","1287":"1287","about 1275":"about 1275","1317":"1317","1328":"1328","Roddam, Northumberland, England":"Roddam, Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Roddam","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Durham and Northumberland): habitational name from Roddam in Ilderton (Northumberland). The placename means ‘at the clearings’, from Old English <i>rodum</i>, dative plural form of <i>rod</i>, <i>rodu</i> ‘clearing’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":15,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLeve